04951nam a22008175i 9780674735903DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013955018  a(OCoLC)1029831794  a(OCoLC)1032694923  a(OCoLC)1037983028  a(OCoLC)1042026432  a(OCoLC)1046616248  a(OCoLC)1046996417  a(OCoLC)979778200  a97806747359037 a10.4159/harvard.97806747359032doi  a(DE-B1597)427404  a(OCoLC)897600345  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aLC89b.L33 2015 7aEDU0160002bisacsh04a3792231 aLaats, Adam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Other School Reformers :bConservative Activism in American Education /cAdam Laats. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (294 p.) :b6 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 What Does Jesus Have to Do with Phonics? -- t2 Monkeys, Morality, and Modern America -- t3 Pulling the Rugg Out -- t4 Rich, Republican, and Reactionary -- t5 Save the Children -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe idea that American education has been steered by progressive values is celebrated by liberals and deplored by conservatives, but both sides accept it as fact. Adam Laats shows that this widely held belief is simply wrong. Upending the standard narrative of American education as the product of courageous progressive reformers, he calls to center stage the conservative activists who decisively shaped America’s classrooms in the twentieth century. The Other School Reformers makes clear that, in the long march of American public education, progressive reform has more often been a beleaguered dream than an insuperable force. Laats takes an in-depth look at four landmark school battles: the 1925 Scopes Trial, the 1939 Rugg textbook controversy, the 1950 ouster of Pasadena Public Schools Superintendent Willard Goslin, and the 1974 Kanawha County school boycott. Focused on issues ranging from evolution to the role of religion in education to the correct interpretation of American history, these four highly publicized controversies forced conservatives to articulate their vision of public schooling—a vision that would keep traditional Protestant beliefs in America’s classrooms and push out subversive subjects like Darwinism, socialism, multiculturalism, and feminism. As Laats makes clear in case after case, activists such as Hiram Evans and Norma Gabler, Homer Chaillaux and Louise Padelford were fiercely committed to a view of the curriculum that inculcated love of country, reinforced traditional gender roles and family structures, allowed no alternatives to capitalism, and granted religion a central role in civic life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConservatismzUnited States. 0aEducationxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aEducational changezUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2015z9783110438741oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067473590340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674735903423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674735903.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  